  "Taxonomy Basics": "分类学基础",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "这个课程涵盖了分析和总结数据集的中心的基本测量方法。 您将学会如何计算和应用平均值、 中位数和模式, 并了解何时最合适 。",
  "What is biodiversity?": "什么是生物多样性?",
  "Biodiversity (biological diversity) was coined by Walter G. Rosen in 1985 and popularized by E.O. Wilson. It operates at three nested levels: genetic diversity (allelic variation within and between populations — the raw material for natural selection), species diversity (measured by both richness and evenness), and ecosystem diversity (the variety of habitats, communities, and ecological processes in a landscape). All three levels are interconnected: genetic diversity enables species to adapt, species diversity stabilizes ecosystems, and ecosystem diversity provides varied niches that support speciation.": "1985年,Walter G. Rosen发明了生物多样性(生物多样性),由E.O.Wilson所普及,在三个嵌巢层次上运作:遗传多样性(人口内部和人口之间的群落变化——自然选择的原材料)、物种多样性(以丰富性和均衡性衡量)和生态系统多样性(生境、社区和景观生态过程的多样性),这三个层次是相互关联的:遗传多样性使物种能够适应,物种多样性稳定了生态系统,生态系统多样性提供了支持物种分化的不同位置。",
  "What is a biodiversity hotspot?": "什么是生物多样性热点?",
  "Norman Myers first identified biodiversity hotspots in 1988, later refined by Conservation International. The 36 recognized hotspots cover only ~2.5% of Earth's land surface yet harbor more than 50% of all plant species and ~43% of bird, mammal, reptile, and amphibian species as endemics. The dual criteria (high endemism + severe threat) make hotspots the most efficient targets for conservation investment — protecting the most irreplaceable species per dollar spent. Examples: Tropical Andes (the richest hotspot), Madagascar and Indian Ocean Islands, the Philippines, the Mediterranean Basin, and the California Floristic Province.": "诺曼·迈尔斯在1988年首次确定了生物多样性热点,后来由国际养护组织加以完善。这36个热点只覆盖了地球陆地表面的2.5%,却将50%以上的植物物种和43%的鸟类、哺乳动物、爬虫类和两栖物种作为地方病。 双重标准(高地方特有和严重威胁)使热点成为保护投资的最有效目标 — — 保护所花费的每美元最不可替代的物种。 例如:热带安第斯山脉(最富的热点 ) 、 马达加斯加和印度洋群岛、菲律宾、地中海盆地和加利福尼亚高地省。",
  "What is the latitudinal diversity gradient?": "纬度多样性梯度是什么?",
  "The latitudinal diversity gradient is one of ecology's most fundamental patterns, documented for plants, insects, birds, mammals, marine invertebrates, and many other groups. Multiple mechanisms contribute: greater solar energy input drives higher productivity, which supports more species and trophic levels; more stable tropical climates enable narrower niche specialization (Janzen's hypothesis); larger tropical area provides more habitat and less extinction; longer evolutionary history without glacial disruption allows more speciation; and stronger biotic interactions (predation, competition, mutualism) in the tropics promote further diversification. No single hypothesis fully explains the gradient.": "纬度多样性梯度是生态中最基本的模式之一,记录了植物、昆虫、鸟类、哺乳动物、海洋无脊椎动物和许多其他群体的情况。多种机制有助于:增加太阳能投入,推动生产力的提高,从而支持更多的物种和营养水平;更稳定的热带气候使得更狭小的特长专业化(Janzen的假设);更大的热带地区提供了更多的栖息地,减少了灭绝;更长期的进化历史,而没有冰川干扰,就使得更多的物种出现;在热带地区,更强大的生物互动(掠夺、竞争、相互影响)能够促进进一步多样化。没有一个单一的假设能充分解释梯度。",
  "What is species richness versus species evenness?": "什么是物种丰富性与物种均衡性?",
  "Consider two forests, each with 100 birds of 10 species. Forest A: 91 of one species + 1 each of nine others. Forest B: 10 of each species. Both have equal richness (10 species), but Forest B has much higher evenness and therefore higher overall diversity (higher Shannon index H'). Evenness matters because communities dominated by one species are less functionally diverse and more vulnerable to disturbance. The Shannon-Wiener index captures both: H' = -Σ(pi × ln pi), where pi is the proportion of each species. Higher H' values indicate higher diversity.": "森林 A : 一种物种中的91种 + 1种,其他9种中各有1种。森林 B : 10种,两种物种都具有同等的丰富性(10种),但森林 B 的均衡性更高,因此总体多样性更高(高香农指数H')。 平衡性很重要,因为由一种物种主导的社区在功能上不那么多样化,更容易受到干扰。 香农- Winer 指数同时捕捉了两种物种: H' =- (pi × in pi), pi 是每种物种的比例。 较高的H 值显示更大的多样性。",
  "What is a keystone species?": "什么是关键物种?",
  "Robert Paine's classic 1966-1969 experiments at Mukkaw Bay, Washington, demonstrated the keystone concept. When he removed the predatory sea star Pisaster ochraceus, the mussel Mytilus californianus outcompeted all other species, reducing community diversity from 15 to 8 species. Other keystone examples: sea otters (control urchins that would otherwise destroy kelp forests), wolves in Yellowstone (control elk browsing, allowing aspen and willow recovery), fig trees in tropical forests (provide year-round fruit for dozens of species), and beavers (create wetland habitats). Losing a keystone species triggers disproportionate ecosystem collapse.": "罗伯特·培恩(Robert Paine)1966-1969年在华盛顿Mukkaw Bay(Mukkaw Bay)的经典实验展示了顶点概念。当他将掠食性海星皮萨斯特(Pisaster ochraceus ) 、 贝贝(Mytilus californianus)和所有其他物种相比,将社区多样性从15个物种减少到8个物种。其他顶点例子:海洋水手(控制海龟(否则会摧毁海藻森林 ) 、 黄石公园中的狼(控制,允许天鹅和柳树恢复 ) 、 热带森林中的无花果树(为数十种提供全年的果实) 和海狸(创造湿地生境 ) 。 失去一个顶点物种会引发过度的生态系统崩溃 。",
  "What is the relationship between island biogeography and biodiversity?": "岛屿生物地理学与生物多样性之间的关系是什么?",
  "MacArthur and Wilson's theory revolutionized both ecology and conservation. Key predictions: (1) species-area relationship — larger islands support more species (S = cAz, where A is area and z ≈ 0.25); (2) distance effect — islands closer to the mainland receive more immigrants; (3) equilibrium — species number stabilizes where immigration rate equals extinction rate, though species composition turns over. Critically, the theory applies to habitat 'islands' — forest fragments, mountain tops, lakes — making it foundational for reserve design. The SLOSS debate (Single Large Or Several Small reserves) directly stems from island biogeography theory.": "MacArthur和Wilson的理论使生态和养护发生革命。主要预测:(1) 物种与地区的关系——较大的岛屿支持更多的物种(S= cAz,其中A为区域,z = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = ;(2) 距离效应—— 距离效应——距离效应——离大陆较近的岛屿的岛屿得到更多移民;(3) = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = =",
  "The Amazon rainforest covers approximately 5.5 million km² across nine South American nations. It contains an estimated 10% of all species on Earth, including 80,000 plant species, 2.5 million insect species, and 2,000 birds and mammals. However, approximately 17% of the Amazon has been deforested since 1970, primarily for cattle ranching and soy farming. Scientists warn that crossing a 20-25% deforestation 'tipping point' could trigger a self-reinforcing transition from rainforest to savanna. What biodiversity concepts does this crisis involve?": "亚马逊雨林覆盖9个南美国家约550万平方公里,占地球上所有物种的10%,包括8万个植物物种、250万昆虫物种和2 000个鸟类和哺乳动物。 然而,自1970年以来,亚马逊约17%的森林被砍伐,主要用于畜牧和大豆养殖。 科学家警告说,超过20-25%的森林砍伐点会引发从雨林到热带雨林的自我强化过渡。 这场危机包含哪些生物多样性概念?",
  "The Amazon crisis integrates multiple biodiversity concepts. The SAR (S = cAz) predicts that losing 40% of forest area could eliminate 12-15% of species (with z ≈ 0.25). The Amazon generates 50% of its own rainfall through transpiration — a 'flying rivers' system where moisture evaporated from trees falls as rain downwind. Crossing the deforestation tipping point could collapse this hydrological cycle, converting moist forest to dry savanna even in undeforested areas. Many Amazonian species are endemic to micro-habitats — single mountaintops, river basins, or forest types — making them especially vulnerable. The Amazon's loss would eliminate ecosystem services worth trillions: carbon storage (150-200 billion metric tons), water regulation, and climate moderation.": "亚马逊危机综合了多种生物多样性概念。 SAR(S = cAz)预测,丧失40%的森林面积可以消灭12-15%的物种(Z ",
  "Lake Malawi in East Africa contains an estimated 700-1,000 species of cichlid fish, nearly all found nowhere else on Earth. These cichlids evolved from a common ancestor in a remarkable example of adaptive radiation — diversifying into rock-dwellers, sand-dwellers, plankton-eaters, snail-crushers, larvae-pickers, and even species that eat the scales of other fish. How does Lake Malawi illustrate the concept of biodiversity at multiple levels?": "东非的马拉维湖含有大约700-1 000种cichlid鱼类,几乎所有的鱼类都在地球上找不到。 这些从一个共同的祖先演变成一个适应性辐射的显著例子 — — 多样化到岩石居民、沙地居民、浮游生物食用者、蜗牛、采食者,甚至食用其他鱼类规模的物种。 马拉维湖如何在多个层面说明生物多样性的概念?",
  "Lake Malawi's cichlids are evolution's most spectacular demonstration of adaptive radiation — rivaling Darwin's finches but with 50× more species produced in 1-2 million years. Genetic diversity: sexual selection on male coloration drives reproductive isolation; even slight color differences can create new species (sympatric speciation). Species diversity: extreme niche partitioning has produced specialists for every conceivable feeding strategy and microhabitat. Ecosystem diversity: the lake's habitat zones (wave-wash rocky zones, deep sediment, open pelagic waters, weedy shallows) function as distinct ecosystems. Threats include overfishing, introduction of non-native species, sedimentation from deforestation, and climate change affecting lake levels. Losing this biodiversity would be like losing the Galápagos — an irreplaceable evolutionary laboratory.": "马拉维湖的晶片是进化中最惊人的适应性辐射示范——与达尔文的鳍相对应,但与在1-2百万年中生产的50×更多的物种相对应。遗传多样性:对男性颜色的性别选择导致生殖隔离;即使是微小的颜色差异也可以创造新的物种(同父异母的物种 )。物种多样性:极端的缝隙分割为每一种可以想象的喂养战略和微生境创造了专家。生态系统多样性:湖泊的生境区(微波洗岩区、深沉积层、开阔的中上层水域、杂草浅)作为不同的生态系统发挥作用。威胁包括过度捕捞、引进非本地物种、毁林造成的沉积以及影响湖泊水平的气候变化。失去这种生物多样性会像失去加拉帕戈斯 — — 一个不可替代的进化实验室。"
